sec.p:
This paper investigated the effect that moderate to ambitious levels of end-use energy efficiency in the EU building sector have on energy system cost and energy supply configurations. The general results indicate that implementing more ambitious energy-saving measures in buildings reduces the total electricity, heat and hydrogen capacities needed to achieve the transition to net-zero GHG emissions. However, according to the indicator of energy system cost (ESC\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ESC$$\end{document}), the ambitious energy savings portrayed in the MediumEff and HighEff scenarios are not necessarily cost-effective compared to the more moderate ambition levels of LowEff. This chapter gives an overview of methodological limitations and discusses policy implications.

Adopting a societal perspective when assessing demand-side and supply-side resources is a key feature of the EE1st principle as this represents the public interest (Mandel et al., 2022c). In this study, the performance indicator of ESC\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
